Dad, what are you doin' here?

244
00:17:01,033 --> 00:17:03,433
I'm robbin' your room,
that's what I'm doin' here.

245
00:17:03,469 --> 00:17:05,232
We drive 300 miles
to see the kid...

246
00:17:05,271 --> 00:17:08,331
that's the greeting we get.
Come here, will ya?

247
00:17:09,742 --> 00:17:11,642
How ya doin' there?

248
00:17:11,677 --> 00:17:13,941
I'm sorry.
I'm really glad to see you...

249
00:17:13,979 --> 00:17:15,742
but I wish
I knew you were coming.

250
00:17:15,781 --> 00:17:17,112
I'll bet you did, huh?

251
00:17:17,149 --> 00:17:18,810
I looked for you
at that fraternity house.

252
00:17:18,851 --> 00:17:21,183
- They said you weren't a member.
- I can explain that.

253
00:17:21,220 --> 00:17:22,551
They also told me
you're not on the diving team.

254
00:17:22,588 --> 00:17:24,647
They said you were
the towel boy.

255
00:17:24,690 --> 00:17:27,022
- I can explain that, too.
- OK, explain it.

256
00:17:27,059 --> 00:17:29,892
- I lied.
- Great. That explains it, huh?

257
00:17:29,929 --> 00:17:33,057
Jason, you don't lie to me.
You lie to girls.

258
00:17:34,500 --> 00:17:35,592
Who's this?

259
00:17:35,634 --> 00:17:37,761
Oh, I'm sorry.
This is my roommate.

260
00:17:37,803 --> 00:17:38,770
That's Derek Lutz.

261
00:17:38,804 --> 00:17:41,534
This is the dad,
and that's Lou.

262
00:17:41,574 --> 00:17:44,065
- Is that your real hair?
- What do you think?

263
00:17:44,110 --> 00:17:47,238
I think you're trying
to get back at your parents.

264
00:17:47,279 --> 00:17:49,406
Show me the campus.
I want to talk to you.

265
00:17:49,448 --> 00:17:50,608
Oh, good.

266
00:17:58,357 --> 00:18:00,382
Boy, what a great-lookin' place.

267
00:18:00,426 --> 00:18:02,189
When I used to dream
about going to college...

268
00:18:02,228 --> 00:18:03,855
this is the way
I always pictured it.

269
00:18:03,896 --> 00:18:05,989
Wait a minute. When did you
dream about going to college?

270
00:18:06,031 --> 00:18:09,296
When I used to fall asleep
in high school.

271
00:18:09,335 --> 00:18:11,269
Dad, I know how much
all this means to you...

272
00:18:11,303 --> 00:18:14,670
- and I'm sorry I lied to you.
- You don't have to lie to me.

273
00:18:14,707 --> 00:18:17,198
No matter what you do,
I'll love you just the same.

274
00:18:17,243 --> 00:18:18,642
Will you love me
no matter what?

275
00:18:18,677 --> 00:18:19,871
No matter what.

276
00:18:19,912 --> 00:18:22,608
- I'm droppin' out.
- You're droppin' out?

277
00:18:22,648 --> 00:18:25,242
You just got here.
You just started.

278
00:18:25,284 --> 00:18:27,252
I know,
but I'm not making it here.

279
00:18:27,286 --> 00:18:29,481
I don't fit in, you know?
I got one friend... Derek.

280
00:18:29,522 --> 00:18:31,547
He's got no friends.

281
00:18:31,590 --> 00:18:34,115
The girls don't like me,
the fraternities don't want me.

282
00:18:34,160 --> 00:18:35,718
The diving coach
won't even talk to me.

283
00:18:35,761 --> 00:18:37,786
Look at it this way...

284
00:18:37,830 --> 00:18:39,798
at least you're getting
an education.

285
00:18:39,832 --> 00:18:42,392
Dad, last semester
I got nothing but "Cs."

286
00:18:42,435 --> 00:18:44,232
A, B, C...
you're in the top three.

287
00:18:44,270 --> 00:18:45,862
What are you worrying about?

288
00:18:45,905 --> 00:18:47,736
I just think I'd be
a lot better off...

289
00:18:47,773 --> 00:18:49,331
gettin' a job or something.

290
00:18:49,375 --> 00:18:51,707
You never went to college.
Look how great you're doin'.

291
00:18:51,744 --> 00:18:54,338
Jason, I said it before
and I'll say it again.

292
00:18:54,380 --> 00:18:56,610
I don't care how rich
and successful a man is.

293
00:18:56,649 --> 00:18:58,241
Without an education,
he's nothing.

294
00:18:58,284 --> 00:19:00,616
I mean, stay in school.
Study harder.

295
00:19:00,653 --> 00:19:02,518
You can be whatever
you want to be.

296
00:19:02,555 --> 00:19:04,022
You want to be a loser,
be a loser.

297
00:19:04,056 --> 00:19:05,148
You want to be a winner,
be a winner.

298
00:19:05,191 --> 00:19:07,421
Jason, it's up to you.
You can do it.

299
00:19:07,460 --> 00:19:10,361
Remember, you're a Melon!

300
00:19:10,396 --> 00:19:14,526
Dad, that's easy for you to say.
You don't have to do any of it.

301
00:19:16,936 --> 00:19:19,268
OK, then.
I'll do it with you.

302
00:19:20,606 --> 00:19:22,096
What do you mean,
you'll do it with me?

303
00:19:22,141 --> 00:19:24,507
I mean just what I said.

304
00:19:24,543 --> 00:19:26,511
I'm going to college.
What do you think?

305
00:19:26,545 --> 00:19:29,013
What do I think?
I think you're nuts.

306
00:19:29,048 --> 00:19:32,848
Nuts, huh? Who made the rules?
Come here. I'm going to college!

307
00:19:32,885 --> 00:19:34,409
I'm going to college!

308
00:19:37,323 --> 00:19:39,917
Let me get this straight,
Mr. Melon.

309
00:19:39,959 --> 00:19:43,486
You wish to enter
this widely esteemed...

310
00:19:43,529 --> 00:19:45,963
Grand Lakes University of ours
as a freshman?

311
00:19:45,998 --> 00:19:47,795
That's right, Dean Martin.

312
00:19:48,934 --> 00:19:52,461
- Are you comfortable?
- I'm fine, yeah.

313
00:19:52,505 --> 00:19:54,564
Oh, the chair. I'm sorry.

314
00:19:57,643 --> 00:20:00,476
This is an awkward moment
for me, Mr. Melon...

315
00:20:00,513 --> 00:20:02,879
since I realize you're
a highly respected member...

316
00:20:02,915 --> 00:20:04,405
of our business community.

317
00:20:04,450 --> 00:20:07,283
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

318
00:20:07,319 --> 00:20:10,880
Our student body here
is handpicked by me...

319
00:20:10,923 --> 00:20:12,390
from the crème de la crème...

320
00:20:12,424 --> 00:20:15,552
of students all across
this great land of ours.

321
00:20:15,594 --> 00:20:17,619
That's one of the things
I like about this place.

322
00:20:17,663 --> 00:20:19,688
Yes. The point is, though...

323
00:20:19,732 --> 00:20:21,700
since you have
no high school diploma...

324
00:20:21,734 --> 00:20:25,170
and no transcripts of any kind,
no S.A.T. Scores...

325
00:20:25,204 --> 00:20:28,901
and you're 30 to 40 years older
than our average freshman...

326
00:20:28,941 --> 00:20:31,671
how can this university
ever see its way clear...

327
00:20:31,710 --> 00:20:34,110
to accept you as a student?

328
00:20:34,146 --> 00:20:36,706
As Calvin Coolidge once said...

329
00:20:36,749 --> 00:20:39,775
"The business of America
is business"...

330
00:20:39,818 --> 00:20:42,343
and the business of
an educational institution...

331
00:20:42,388 --> 00:20:45,016
such as ours
is to create young minds...

332
00:20:45,057 --> 00:20:46,957
that understand that
the business of America...

333
00:20:46,992 --> 00:20:50,689
is the kind of business
that it actually is.

334
00:20:50,729 --> 00:20:54,722
So, whatever it is that
I have said here today...

335
00:20:54,767 --> 00:20:59,397
the point is
that we are here to honor...

336
00:20:59,438 --> 00:21:02,532
our most generous benefactor...

337
00:21:02,575 --> 00:21:05,305
and newest freshman...

338
00:21:05,344 --> 00:21:07,107
the man who's
made it possible...

339
00:21:07,146 --> 00:21:10,047
for us to break ground
here today...

340
00:21:10,082 --> 00:21:12,380
Mr. Thornton Melon.

341
00:21:15,521 --> 00:21:17,887
Dean Martin, great speech.

342
00:21:17,923 --> 00:21:20,289
There's nothing like good,
clean business, huh?

343
00:21:20,326 --> 00:21:23,386
And a little monkey business.

344
00:21:23,429 --> 00:21:26,660
Oh, Philip. I'm so glad
you could make it.

345
00:21:26,699 --> 00:21:29,099
Mr. Melon, I'd like for you
to meet Dr. Philip Barbay...

346
00:21:29,134 --> 00:21:33,195
who's the dean
of our school of business.

347
00:21:33,238 --> 00:21:35,001
David, I just want
to get it on record...

348
00:21:35,040 --> 00:21:36,632
that I am totally against this.

349
00:21:36,675 --> 00:21:38,802
I don't think
that selling admission...

350
00:21:38,844 --> 00:21:40,903
to an obviously
unqualified student...

351
00:21:40,946 --> 00:21:43,437
is very ethical or honorable.

352
00:21:43,482 --> 00:21:47,009
Right, Phil,
but I'd just like to say...

353
00:21:47,052 --> 00:21:49,350
in all fairness
to Mr. Melon here...

354
00:21:49,388 --> 00:21:52,357
it was a really big check.

355
00:21:52,391 --> 00:21:54,484
It's a simple matter
of this man's presence...

356
00:21:54,526 --> 00:21:57,495
undermining the efforts
of our legitimate students...

357
00:21:57,529 --> 00:21:59,497
who are here as a result
of hard work.

358
00:21:59,531 --> 00:22:00,828
Hard work?

359
00:22:00,866 --> 00:22:03,562
Listen, Sherlock, while you were
tucked away up here...

360
00:22:03,602 --> 00:22:05,570
working on your ethics,
I was out there...

361
00:22:05,604 --> 00:22:07,629
busting my hump
in the real world.

362
00:22:07,673 --> 00:22:09,868
And the reason guys like you
got a place to teach...

363
00:22:09,908 --> 00:22:12,001
is 'cause guys like me
donate buildings.

364
00:22:12,044 --> 00:22:15,275
I wasn't speaking to you,
Mr. Melon.

365
00:22:22,254 --> 00:22:24,518
I don't think
Dr. Barbay understands...

366
00:22:24,556 --> 00:22:27,389
the actual amounts
that are involved here.

367
00:22:27,426 --> 00:22:31,658
Mr. Melon, will you take
the ceremonial shovel?

368
00:22:31,697 --> 00:22:32,664
Thank you.

369
00:22:32,698 --> 00:22:35,565
And dig into the symbolic dirt.

370
00:22:38,203 --> 00:22:43,163
I hereby dedicate
this building to... myself.

371
00:22:55,387 --> 00:22:57,378
Now, Dad, it's just like
we talked about.

372
00:22:57,423 --> 00:22:59,391
You sign up for whatever
interests you, OK?

373
00:22:59,425 --> 00:23:01,154
We're gonna get
on the astronomy line...

374
00:23:01,193 --> 00:23:03,184
before it closes up.
See you later.

375
00:23:04,997 --> 00:23:08,956
Look at this.
This is worse than the track.

376
00:23:09,001 --> 00:23:10,593
You want me to move
some people for you?

377
00:23:10,636 --> 00:23:11,694
No, don't push anybody around.

378
00:23:11,737 --> 00:23:14,331
This is college.
Let me think for a minute.

379
00:23:14,373 --> 00:23:15,965
What are you gonna do?

380
00:23:16,008 --> 00:23:18,374
Come on. I got an idea.

381
00:23:18,410 --> 00:23:19,377
Did you get
everything you want?

382
00:23:19,411 --> 00:23:22,107
I got the Latin
and the Sanskrit...

383
00:23:22,147 --> 00:23:23,774
but then they canceled
my Ancient Greek.

384
00:23:23,816 --> 00:23:25,784
Just blew my whole
dead languages motif.

385
00:23:25,818 --> 00:23:27,945
What are you looking at?

386
00:23:41,867 --> 00:23:44,267
You OK?

387
00:23:44,303 --> 00:23:47,830
Yeah. Yeah, I'm fine.

388
00:23:47,873 --> 00:23:50,239
I'm just upset
because they closed botany.

389
00:23:50,275 --> 00:23:52,243
Those bastards!

390
00:23:52,277 --> 00:23:54,438
Well, I'm not that upset.

391
00:23:55,781 --> 00:23:58,511
At least, I won't be
if I get into astronomy.

392
00:23:58,550 --> 00:24:00,848
You want to cut
into line with us?

393
00:24:00,886 --> 00:24:01,944
'Cause we're already waiting.

394
00:24:01,987 --> 00:24:04,820
Yes. Yeah, I would.

395
00:24:04,857 --> 00:24:05,949
Great. All right.

396
00:24:09,862 --> 00:24:11,727
Oh, this is Derek.

397
00:24:11,764 --> 00:24:14,597
Hi.

398
00:24:14,633 --> 00:24:16,430
I'm Valerie Desmond.

399
00:24:16,468 --> 00:24:18,459
Yeah, I know.

400
00:24:19,838 --> 00:24:22,807
- I'm Jason Melon.
- Hi.

401
00:24:26,879 --> 00:24:29,109
- Hey, Valerie.
- Hi.

402
00:24:29,148 --> 00:24:30,615
God, you look great.

403
00:24:30,649 --> 00:24:33,243
Thanks. Are you taking
astronomy, too?

404
00:24:33,285 --> 00:24:35,185
Yeah, I guess so.

405
00:24:35,220 --> 00:24:37,279
I don't really want to.
I'm a business major.

406
00:24:37,322 --> 00:24:40,348
But for some reason,
they want us to take a science.

407
00:24:40,392 --> 00:24:42,360
You mind if I sneak
in the line with you?

408
00:24:42,394 --> 00:24:45,295
Actually, these guys were
nice enough to let me in...

409
00:24:45,330 --> 00:24:48,731
so it's really
up to them, I guess.

410
00:24:48,767 --> 00:24:50,530
Melon, buddy?

411
00:24:50,569 --> 00:24:53,060
Whaddaya say? Let me in, OK?

412
00:24:53,105 --> 00:24:55,539
I don't think so, Osbourne.

413
00:24:55,574 --> 00:24:57,633
Melon, your friend...
straighten him out.

414
00:24:57,676 --> 00:24:59,268
Look, Chas,
there's a lot of people waiting.

415
00:24:59,311 --> 00:25:01,905
It wouldn't really be fair.

416
00:25:01,947 --> 00:25:03,107
I'll tell you what.

417
00:25:03,148 --> 00:25:07,209
Maybe if you got a note
from each of these people...

418
00:25:07,252 --> 00:25:09,379
saying that it was all right,
then we'd reconsider...

419
00:25:09,421 --> 00:25:11,218
but until that day,
take a hike...

420
00:25:11,256 --> 00:25:14,350
you elitist fraternity scumbag.

421
00:25:18,030 --> 00:25:20,089
I won't forget this, Melon.

422
00:25:20,132 --> 00:25:21,895
I'll see you at the pool.

423
00:25:21,934 --> 00:25:23,299
- Bye, Val.
- Bye.

424
00:25:23,335 --> 00:25:24,927
Thank you. I'm dead.

425
00:25:24,970 --> 00:25:26,938
You're not gonna believe this!

426
00:25:26,972 --> 00:25:29,566
- You're kidding!
- I'm not kidding! Just go!

427
00:25:29,608 --> 00:25:31,269
He's out there!

428
00:25:41,453 --> 00:25:44,854
Bruce! Bruce! Bruce! Bruce!

429
00:25:49,795 --> 00:25:51,194
Where is he?

430
00:25:51,230 --> 00:25:52,356
I don't know, kid.

431
00:25:52,397 --> 00:25:54,092
All I know is I'm supposed
to pick him up here.

432
00:25:54,132 --> 00:25:56,100
- When?
- Now.

433
00:25:56,134 --> 00:25:58,830
Come on, let's register.

434
00:26:07,512 --> 00:26:09,036
Hey, you guys
get everything you need?

435
00:26:09,081 --> 00:26:10,343
Oh, yeah, we got it.

436
00:26:10,382 --> 00:26:11,974
Good. What's with
the used books?

437
00:26:12,017 --> 00:26:14,417
- What's wrong with used books?
- They've already been read.

438
00:26:14,453 --> 00:26:16,250
And they've already been
underlined.

439
00:26:16,288 --> 00:26:17,516
That's the problem.

440
00:26:17,556 --> 00:26:19,786
The guy who underlined them
could have been a maniac.

441
00:26:19,825 --> 00:26:23,124
Get these guys some new books.

442
00:26:23,161 --> 00:26:26,096
Charge it to me, too.
Here, pick a card.

443
00:26:27,299 --> 00:26:30,132
And I'm taking four
of those school sweaters...

444
00:26:30,168 --> 00:26:32,864
a bunch of pennants,
some of those beer mugs...

445
00:26:32,905 --> 00:26:35,499
a few of these fuzz balls
you cheer with, and...

446
00:26:35,540 --> 00:26:38,771
Hey, folks, it's on me!
Shakespeare for everyone, OK?

447
00:26:40,379 --> 00:26:43,314
You, too, honey.
I'd like to tame your shrew.

448
00:26:43,348 --> 00:26:47,182
- Who is that?
- That is Mr. Thornton Melon...

449
00:26:47,219 --> 00:26:49,881
the world's oldest
living freshman...

450
00:26:49,922 --> 00:26:52,948
and the walking epitome of
the decline of modern education.

451
00:26:52,991 --> 00:26:55,391
The stupid clod thinks he can
buy his way out of the gutter.

452
00:26:55,427 --> 00:26:57,725
I don't think so.
He was just having fun.

453
00:26:57,763 --> 00:27:02,427
Oh, really? Well, I can't wait
to get him in my class.

454
00:27:02,467 --> 00:27:04,594
We'll see how much fun
he is then.

455
00:27:04,636 --> 00:27:05,796
Oh, Philip.

456
00:27:05,837 --> 00:27:08,863
Hey, Mr. M! You're all set.
We've been working all night.

457
00:27:08,907 --> 00:27:10,465
We got it all done.

458
00:27:10,509 --> 00:27:12,340
Thanks, Buzzy.
I appreciate it.

459
00:27:12,377 --> 00:27:15,676
Add a few hundred to the bill
and throw your boys a party.

460
00:27:15,714 --> 00:27:18,842
You know what you got, Mr. M?
You got class.

461
00:27:18,884 --> 00:27:22,081
It rubbed off from you, Buzzy.
Say hello to Sonia for me, huh?

462
00:27:22,120 --> 00:27:23,314
You got it.

463
00:27:23,355 --> 00:27:26,256
I want to talk to you
about my schedule.

464
00:27:26,291 --> 00:27:28,452
We'll go over it later.

465
00:27:41,273 --> 00:27:43,605
Well, boys,
what do you think?

466
00:27:43,642 --> 00:27:45,507
Got a hot tub in there!

467
00:27:45,544 --> 00:27:47,705
How can you study
if you're not relaxed?

468
00:27:47,746 --> 00:27:48,906
When's our first class?

469
00:27:48,947 --> 00:27:51,108
We got economics
tomorrow at 11:00.

470
00:27:51,149 --> 00:27:52,309
11:00? No good.

471
00:27:52,351 --> 00:27:54,512
I got a massage at 11:00.
Tell them to make it 2:00.

472
00:27:54,553 --> 00:27:57,716
No, Dad, you don't get it.

473
00:27:57,756 --> 00:28:01,886
They're not gonna reschedule
the classes around your massage.

474
00:28:01,927 --> 00:28:04,487
All right, 11:00.
But I'm gonna talk to that dean.

475
00:28:04,529 --> 00:28:07,020
These classes can be
a real inconvenience.

476
00:28:07,065 --> 00:28:09,533
All right, settle down, people.

477
00:28:09,568 --> 00:28:12,560
We've got a lot to cover,
and time is short.

478
00:28:16,375 --> 00:28:19,401
There are two kinds of people
in business today...

479
00:28:19,444 --> 00:28:21,412
the quick and the dead.

480
00:28:21,446 --> 00:28:24,574
So, rather than waste
your time this semester...

481
00:28:24,616 --> 00:28:27,050
with a lot of
useless theories...

482
00:28:27,085 --> 00:28:29,110
we're going to jump right in
with both feet...

483
00:28:29,154 --> 00:28:32,055
and create a fictional company
from the ground up.

484
00:28:32,090 --> 00:28:35,116
We'll construct
our physical plant...

485
00:28:35,160 --> 00:28:37,560
we'll set up
an efficient administrative...

486
00:28:37,596 --> 00:28:39,393
and executive structure...

487
00:28:39,431 --> 00:28:43,026
