842
00:47:17,574 --> 00:47:21,510
and when I get upset,
he gets physical.

843
00:47:28,919 --> 00:47:30,443
You got a problem?

844
00:47:30,487 --> 00:47:32,512
No, I haven't got a problem.

845
00:47:32,556 --> 00:47:34,922
Now you do.

846
00:47:45,502 --> 00:47:46,901
Get him!

847
00:47:58,615 --> 00:47:59,809
Lou, where you been?

848
00:47:59,850 --> 00:48:01,715
I'm getting my ass kicked
all over the place!

849
00:48:27,578 --> 00:48:30,342
- Well, you look terrible.
- No, I'm all right.

850
00:48:30,381 --> 00:48:34,147
It's Lou I'm worried about.
He may lose his trigger finger.

851
00:48:34,184 --> 00:48:35,446
It serves you guys right.

852
00:48:35,486 --> 00:48:37,545
Why did you have to take on
the whole football team?

853
00:48:37,588 --> 00:48:38,748
They're not that tough.

854
00:48:38,789 --> 00:48:41,121
The football team
at my high school was tough.

855
00:48:41,158 --> 00:48:42,785
After they sacked
the quarterback...

856
00:48:42,826 --> 00:48:44,691
they went after his family.

857
00:48:47,064 --> 00:48:49,259
This morning we're going to look
at "The Great Gatsby"...

858
00:48:49,299 --> 00:48:51,460
by F. Scott Fitzgerald.

859
00:48:51,502 --> 00:48:54,903
Mr. Melon, how would you
characterize "The Great Gatsby?"

860
00:48:54,938 --> 00:48:56,872
Who, him?

861
00:48:56,907 --> 00:48:58,340
No, you.

862
00:48:58,375 --> 00:48:59,774
Me.

863
00:48:59,810 --> 00:49:02,870
Well, "The Great Gatsby,"
he was...

864
00:49:02,913 --> 00:49:05,108
great.

865
00:49:08,252 --> 00:49:09,844
See me after class, Mr. Melon.

866
00:49:13,857 --> 00:49:15,722
I mean, please,
try to understand.

867
00:49:15,759 --> 00:49:17,317
I don't have
the background for this.

868
00:49:17,361 --> 00:49:18,623
The high school I went to...

869
00:49:18,662 --> 00:49:20,323
they asked a kid to prove
the law of gravity.

870
00:49:20,364 --> 00:49:22,662
He threw the teacher
out the window.

871
00:49:22,699 --> 00:49:27,898
I know what I need.
I need a tutor.

872
00:49:27,938 --> 00:49:30,406
What do you say? Come on.

873
00:49:30,441 --> 00:49:33,001
You got some spare time.

874
00:49:33,043 --> 00:49:34,374
All right, Mr. Melon.

875
00:49:34,411 --> 00:49:36,174
I have some spare time
this evening.

876
00:49:36,213 --> 00:49:38,374
Why don't you come around
about 7:00?

877
00:49:38,415 --> 00:49:41,009
- Great.
- I'll give you my address.

878
00:49:42,186 --> 00:49:44,552
- Thanks.
- Please be on time.

879
00:49:44,588 --> 00:49:47,022
I'll be on time.

880
00:49:48,826 --> 00:49:50,760
What penmanship.

881
00:49:52,196 --> 00:49:55,893
"Everywhere the ceremony
of innocence is drowned;

882
00:49:55,933 --> 00:49:57,594
"The best
lack all conviction...

883
00:49:57,634 --> 00:50:00,899
"while the worst are full
of passionate intensity."

884
00:50:00,938 --> 00:50:02,530
There's a lot
of other stuff here.

885
00:50:02,573 --> 00:50:06,771
Yeats goes on and on...
and here's the finish.

886
00:50:06,810 --> 00:50:09,973
"What rough beast,
its hour come round at last...

887
00:50:10,013 --> 00:50:12,914
"slouches towards Bethlehem
to be born?"

888
00:50:12,950 --> 00:50:14,577
What does that
make you think of?

889
00:50:14,618 --> 00:50:17,610
Rough beast. My ex-wife.

890
00:50:17,654 --> 00:50:18,985
Well, that's
one interpretation.

891
00:50:19,022 --> 00:50:21,013
Not the right one,
but it's a start.

892
00:50:21,058 --> 00:50:23,390
Surely a man of your age
and experience...

893
00:50:23,427 --> 00:50:25,088
must have read some
of the things on my list.

894
00:50:25,129 --> 00:50:27,757
- What about "Macbeth"?
- I saw the movie.

895
00:50:27,798 --> 00:50:30,892
Orson Welles.
Great actor, big actor.

896
00:50:30,934 --> 00:50:33,402
He was a Tall and Fat
customer for years.

897
00:50:33,437 --> 00:50:34,699
How about
"Cat on a Hot Tin Roof"?

898
00:50:34,738 --> 00:50:36,672
I saw the movie. Burl lves.

899
00:50:36,707 --> 00:50:40,234
Great actor, extra stout.
He was a customer, too.

900
00:50:40,277 --> 00:50:42,939
- "Streetcar Named Desire."
- Great movie. Marlon Brando.

901
00:50:42,980 --> 00:50:46,541
He wasn't that big then,
but he ballooned up nicely.

902
00:50:46,583 --> 00:50:49,245
I'd say pound for pound,
our finest American actor.

903
00:50:49,286 --> 00:50:51,254
Don't you ever read?

904
00:50:51,288 --> 00:50:54,849
