973
00:54:14,858 --> 00:54:17,986
Me, too.
And thanks for the lesson.

974
00:54:18,028 --> 00:54:19,495
I learned a lot.

975
00:54:19,529 --> 00:54:22,157
You're welcome. I did, too.

976
00:54:24,034 --> 00:54:25,262
Well...

977
00:54:26,403 --> 00:54:29,861
Well, I guess
this is good night.

978
00:54:29,906 --> 00:54:31,237
Yeah.

979
00:54:33,243 --> 00:54:35,370
A very good night.

980
00:54:42,152 --> 00:54:43,483
Beautiful.

981
00:54:45,389 --> 00:54:46,686
Oh, that's it.

982
00:54:46,723 --> 00:54:49,089
That's the spot.
Just keep doing that.

983
00:54:49,126 --> 00:54:52,095
Oh, don't lose it.

984
00:54:52,129 --> 00:54:54,324
Oh, Lou, you're great.

985
00:54:54,364 --> 00:54:57,265
The leg is better.
You got the cramp out.

986
00:54:57,300 --> 00:55:00,701
You're a wreck.
You gotta start working out.

987
00:55:00,737 --> 00:55:02,500
And you know what else?

988
00:55:02,539 --> 00:55:05,406
You have got midterms
coming up.

989
00:55:05,442 --> 00:55:08,070
You haven't studied five minutes
since you got here.

990
00:55:08,111 --> 00:55:09,271
You're always so neat.

991
00:55:09,312 --> 00:55:11,212
You're just like
your Uncle Vito.

992
00:55:11,248 --> 00:55:13,842
We were kids,
his room was always in order.

993
00:55:13,884 --> 00:55:15,044
His towels lined up neatly...

994
00:55:15,085 --> 00:55:17,246
combs, brushes, hair lotions
all in the right place.

995
00:55:17,287 --> 00:55:19,255
What did it mean?
What is he today?

996
00:55:19,289 --> 00:55:20,847
He's an attendant
in the men's room.

997
00:55:20,891 --> 00:55:23,291
Hey, he's my idol.

998
00:55:23,326 --> 00:55:28,559
But I'm not gonna be
folding towels anymore...

999
00:55:28,598 --> 00:55:31,761
'cause I just made...
ta da... the diving team.

1000
00:55:31,802 --> 00:55:34,430
That's great!

1001
00:55:34,471 --> 00:55:35,631
I'm takin' you out.

1002
00:55:35,672 --> 00:55:37,367
We'll celebrate.
We're havin' a party!

1003
00:55:37,407 --> 00:55:40,001
Oh, no, Dad, that's really nice,
but I'm in training now.

1004
00:55:40,043 --> 00:55:42,511
We got a big meet coming up
against Northern.

1005
00:55:42,546 --> 00:55:44,605
We'll have a party
after the meet.

1006
00:55:44,648 --> 00:55:48,584
Dad, why don't you join me
on a little reality break, OK?

1007
00:55:48,618 --> 00:55:50,984
Just 'cause you're in love
with Dr. Turner...

1008
00:55:51,021 --> 00:55:53,785
does not mean you're
gonna pass her course.

1009
00:55:53,824 --> 00:55:56,418
You got a major paper
coming up on Kurt Vonnegut.

1010
00:55:56,460 --> 00:55:58,257
You haven't even read
any of the books.

1011
00:55:58,295 --> 00:55:59,956
I tried.

1012
00:55:59,996 --> 00:56:03,159
I don't understand
a word of it.

1013
00:56:04,167 --> 00:56:07,159
So, how you gonna
write the paper, then?

1014
00:56:11,174 --> 00:56:14,439
Hi, I'm Kurt Vonnegut.
I'm looking for Thornton Melon.

1015
00:56:17,147 --> 00:56:19,775
Want to come in? Dad?

1016
00:56:22,819 --> 00:56:25,617
I don't want to hear
one more word out of you...

1017
00:56:25,655 --> 00:56:27,623
or it's back to the tree.

1018
00:56:27,657 --> 00:56:29,989
Come in.

1019
00:56:30,026 --> 00:56:33,018
Excuse me. Dr. Barazini?

1020
00:56:33,063 --> 00:56:34,428
I'm Thornton Melon.

1021
00:56:34,464 --> 00:56:37,991
Oh, yes, Thornton Melon.
I know you.

1022
00:56:38,034 --> 00:56:41,629
You delivered the paper
on isomagnetic brain waves...

1023
00:56:41,671 --> 00:56:43,229
in Montreal last year.

1024
00:56:43,273 --> 00:56:45,833
No, I sold you your pants.

1025
00:56:45,876 --> 00:56:47,935
Oh, of course.
Good to see you.

1026
00:56:47,978 --> 00:56:49,502
What are you doing here?

1027
00:56:49,546 --> 00:56:51,912
I'm supposed to report here
for my lab project.

1028
00:56:51,948 --> 00:56:54,781
Oh, good. I'm trying to teach
these here apes...

1029
00:56:54,818 --> 00:56:56,649
how to read and write.

1030
00:56:56,686 --> 00:56:59,484
You ought to teach them
how to go to the bathroom.

1031
00:56:59,523 --> 00:57:01,582
You'll get used to that.

1032
00:57:01,625 --> 00:57:06,392
Now, all you have to do
is put a new tape...

1033
00:57:06,429 --> 00:57:10,058
in the tape machine every hour
and observe the animals.

1034
00:57:10,100 --> 00:57:12,261
I'll be back in a few hours
to check on you.

1035
00:57:12,302 --> 00:57:14,862
- OK, fine.
- All righty.

1036
00:57:16,706 --> 00:57:20,039
You don't need this.
I'll find you an organ grinder.

1037
00:57:29,986 --> 00:57:32,147
Hiya, Marge?
A few things.

1038
00:57:32,188 --> 00:57:34,850
I need you and the gang to get
down here as fast as you can.

1039
00:57:34,891 --> 00:57:36,518
And I have to talk to Peterson,
the accountant.

1040
00:57:36,560 --> 00:57:37,925
I'm gonna need him, too.

1041
00:57:37,961 --> 00:57:41,260
Oh, thanks.
And, Marge, I need...

1042
00:57:44,200 --> 00:57:46,498
See if you can get somebody
at the Rand Corporation...

1043
00:57:46,536 --> 00:57:49,403
or the Brookings Institute to
come down here for about a week.

1044
00:57:51,975 --> 00:57:53,169
What?

1045
00:57:55,045 --> 00:57:58,037
And Russell hits him
with a powerful front body slam!

1046
00:58:03,019 --> 00:58:04,316
No problem.

1047
00:58:04,354 --> 00:58:06,754
They're takin' a break,
that's all.

1048
00:58:08,258 --> 00:58:12,490
In 1971, the United States
accumulated deficits...

1049
00:58:12,529 --> 00:58:15,464
greater than the supply
of gold the country held.

1050
00:58:15,498 --> 00:58:18,194
In that year, Richard Nixon...

1051
00:58:18,234 --> 00:58:21,169
took the United States
off the gold standard.

1052
00:58:21,204 --> 00:58:23,536
In doing so, he disrupted...

1053
00:58:26,242 --> 00:58:29,177
the entire international
monetary system.

1054
00:58:29,212 --> 00:58:31,942
What is that clicking noise?

1055
00:58:37,053 --> 00:58:39,112
Are you a student
in this class?

1056
00:58:40,957 --> 00:58:42,356
No.

1057
00:58:42,392 --> 00:58:44,917
Who are you?

1058
00:58:44,961 --> 00:58:48,226
I'm Marge Sweetwater...

1059
00:58:48,264 --> 00:58:50,562
Mr. Thornton Melon's
private secretary.

1060
00:58:57,607 --> 00:59:00,599
What are you doing here?

1061
00:59:00,644 --> 00:59:04,045
I'm taking notes for Mr. Melon.

1062
00:59:07,784 --> 00:59:12,016
He told you to write down
everything I say?

1063
00:59:12,055 --> 00:59:14,785
Yes, he did.

1064
00:59:14,824 --> 00:59:16,257
Good.

1065
00:59:18,695 --> 00:59:20,993
Take this down.

1066
00:59:23,733 --> 00:59:27,100
Mr. Melon,
no matter what you do...

1067
00:59:28,672 --> 00:59:31,539
no matter what stunts
you pull...

1068
00:59:31,574 --> 00:59:34,702
no matter how hard you try...

1069
00:59:34,744 --> 00:59:39,204
you will never, ever
pass this course.

1070
00:59:42,152 --> 00:59:44,620
Make sure he gets that.

1071
00:59:47,691 --> 00:59:49,659
Yes, sir.

1072
00:59:49,693 --> 00:59:50,853
I'll tell you what.

1073
00:59:50,894 --> 00:59:53,124
It's for Barbay.
Make it an "A."

1074
00:59:53,163 --> 00:59:55,324
Where's the lab report
on psychology?

1075
00:59:55,365 --> 00:59:56,696
Here.

1076
00:59:58,702 --> 01:00:01,865
It's too light.
It feels like a "C."

1077
01:00:01,905 --> 01:00:05,170
Bulk it up and add a few
multicolored graphs.

1078
01:00:05,208 --> 01:00:07,836
- Yo, Dad.
- Jason, hold it, will ya?

1079
01:00:07,877 --> 01:00:10,573
Listen, everybody.
Let's see "As" across the board.

1080
01:00:10,613 --> 01:00:11,773
I'll tell you what...

1081
01:00:11,815 --> 01:00:14,215
a ten percent bonus
for every grade over "B."

1082
01:00:14,250 --> 01:00:18,812
And an A+ gets you a free trip
to Hawaii... off-season.

1083
01:00:20,356 --> 01:00:24,190
- Dad, what's going on here?
- I'm doing my homework.

1084
01:00:24,227 --> 01:00:26,422
No, they're doing
your homework.

1085
01:00:26,463 --> 01:00:29,398
A good executive knows how
to delegate authority.

1086
01:00:29,432 --> 01:00:32,026
I took care of you, too.

1087
01:00:32,068 --> 01:00:35,834
- And what's this?
- Your astronomy report.

1088
01:00:35,872 --> 01:00:38,363
- What's wrong with you?
- What's wrong with you?

1089
01:00:38,408 --> 01:00:40,774
I want to write that paper.
I'm gonna write that paper.

1090
01:00:40,810 --> 01:00:43,301
That's why I'm taking astronomy,
to learn something!

1091
01:00:43,346 --> 01:00:45,314
You're never gonna learn
a goddamn thing...

1092
01:00:45,348 --> 01:00:47,373
if you got people
doing your work for you!

1093
01:00:47,417 --> 01:00:49,317
Oh, never mind.

1094
01:00:50,720 --> 01:00:55,350
Kids... they always do things
the hard way.

1095
01:00:55,391 --> 01:00:59,259
Ladies and gentlemen,
the visiting team...

1096
01:00:59,295 --> 01:01:02,594
the Northern University
Wildcats!

1097
01:01:04,067 --> 01:01:08,561
And your Grand Lakes
University Hooters!

1098
01:01:08,605 --> 01:01:11,369
- Hey, there's your boy!
- Jason!

1099
01:01:15,445 --> 01:01:18,573
While the teams are warming up,
we'd like to remind you...

1100
01:01:18,615 --> 01:01:20,674
that all proceeds
from the refreshment stands...

1101
01:01:20,717 --> 01:01:22,412
go to your student government.

1102
01:01:22,452 --> 01:01:25,421
Hey, Valerie. How you doin'?

1103
01:01:25,455 --> 01:01:27,548
Glad you could come. Listen.

1104
01:01:27,590 --> 01:01:30,525
My dad is having a party
tonight at the dorm...

1105
01:01:30,560 --> 01:01:33,461
and it should be pretty great.
His parties usually are.

1106
01:01:33,496 --> 01:01:38,195
I'd love to come,
except for I have a date.

1107
01:01:38,234 --> 01:01:41,692
Oh. Well, hey, bring him along.

1108
01:01:41,738 --> 01:01:44,229
It's OK.
You just both come by.

1109
01:01:44,274 --> 01:01:46,139
I'll really try.

1110
01:01:46,176 --> 01:01:48,144
Good. I hope
I'll see you there.

1111
01:01:48,178 --> 01:01:51,272
It sounds like fun. I wish
my dad were more like yours.

1112
01:02:01,958 --> 01:02:04,586
Hey, Chas.

1113
01:02:04,627 --> 01:02:06,390
Good luck, buddy.
Let's get them.

1114
01:02:06,429 --> 01:02:10,024
Yeah. Thanks, Melon.
I'd wish you luck, too...

1115
01:02:10,066 --> 01:02:12,091
but I guess a guy like you
doesn't need luck.

1116
01:02:13,102 --> 01:02:15,093
What's that supposed to mean?

1117
01:02:15,138 --> 01:02:17,197
With your old man behind you...

1118
01:02:17,240 --> 01:02:19,765
I figured since he bought
your way onto the team...

1119
01:02:19,809 --> 01:02:22,277
he probably bought off
the judges, too.

1120
01:02:26,349 --> 01:02:28,977
Oh, there's Thornton.

1121
01:02:29,018 --> 01:02:31,111
Diane!

1122
01:02:32,722 --> 01:02:36,180
I can't imagine what you can
possibly see in that man.

1123
01:02:36,226 --> 01:02:39,457
Philip, would you excuse me
for a minute?

1124
01:02:43,333 --> 01:02:45,358
Yes, yes.

1125
01:02:45,401 --> 01:02:47,426
- You look great.
- Oh, thanks.

1126
01:02:47,470 --> 01:02:49,267
Where you been?
I called you a hundred times.

1127
01:02:49,305 --> 01:02:51,273
I made four dates
with your answering machine.

1128
01:02:51,307 --> 01:02:53,298
I'm sorry I missed you.
Things have been so hectic.

1129
01:02:53,343 --> 01:02:56,176
I've been reading midterm papers
and grading exams.

1130
01:02:56,212 --> 01:02:57,440
Did you read mine yet?

1131
01:02:57,480 --> 01:02:59,345
Not yet,
but I'm looking forward to it.

1132
01:02:59,382 --> 01:03:01,247
I'm throwing a party
in our room tonight...

1133
01:03:01,284 --> 01:03:02,774
and you better be there.

1134
01:03:02,819 --> 01:03:05,811
I'm sorry. I have a date
with Philip tonight.

1135
01:03:05,855 --> 01:03:09,518
Bring him along.
We may run out of ice.

1136
01:03:12,228 --> 01:03:16,324
First diver
for Grand Lakes University...

1137
01:03:16,366 --> 01:03:18,630
Chas Osbourne.

1138
01:03:41,791 --> 01:03:45,420
Hey, Coach! How are ya?
How you doin', huh?

1139
01:03:50,066 --> 01:03:55,299
Next diver for Grand Lakes...
Jason Melon.

1140
01:03:55,338 --> 01:03:57,636
Melon.

1141
01:04:42,885 --> 01:04:43,977
What's going on?

1142
01:04:44,020 --> 01:04:45,749
This is always
the best party of the year.

1143
01:04:45,788 --> 01:04:48,416
I don't know.
Some big event at the dorms.

1144
01:04:48,458 --> 01:04:52,019
- We're thinkin' of going over.
- To Melon's? Are you nuts?

1145
01:04:52,061 --> 01:04:53,528
Why don't we go?

1146
01:04:53,563 --> 01:04:55,394
Valerie, please.
It'll be horrible.

1147
01:04:55,431 --> 01:04:58,127
Jason said it would be great.
It might be fun.

1148
01:04:58,167 --> 01:05:01,466
Jason's a twerp. We could have
won if it weren't for him.

1149
01:05:01,504 --> 01:05:04,166
Haven't you ever messed up?

1150
01:05:04,207 --> 01:05:05,401
No.

1151
01:05:10,413 --> 01:05:15,043
I'm all dressed up
with nowhere to go

1152
01:05:15,084 --> 01:05:16,813
Hey, baby!

1153
01:05:16,853 --> 01:05:20,084
Walking with a dead man
over my shoulder

1154
01:05:22,859 --> 01:05:25,657
I'm all dressed up
with nowhere to go

1155
01:05:27,997 --> 01:05:30,261
I love three girls at once.

1156
01:05:30,299 --> 01:05:33,359
If I fall asleep,
they have each other to talk to.

1157
01:05:41,044 --> 01:05:43,342
Nice look.
What are you going for?

1158
01:05:43,379 --> 01:05:45,745
The heavy, disassociated
artist thing...

1159
01:05:45,782 --> 01:05:49,548
or the "I'm going blind" thing?

1160
01:05:49,585 --> 01:05:53,521
Oh, It's the deaf thing.
Maybe this will cheer you up.

1161
01:05:53,556 --> 01:05:55,956
Oh, do me!

1162
01:05:55,992 --> 01:05:57,653
Derek! Get up, will ya?

1163
01:05:57,693 --> 01:06:00,856
You look like the poster boy
for birth control.

1164
01:06:04,567 --> 01:06:07,035
Jason, it's a party.
What's your story?

1165
01:06:07,070 --> 01:06:09,038
What's the matter?
The swim meet?

1166
01:06:09,072 --> 01:06:13,031
Forget about it. It's history.

1167
01:06:13,076 --> 01:06:15,442
Come on, will ya? Snap into it!

1168
01:06:15,478 --> 01:06:17,810
You're right, Dad.
It doesn't matter, Dad!

1169
01:06:17,847 --> 01:06:19,940
Right, Dad?
Come on, party, right?

1170
01:06:27,423 --> 01:06:29,618
Hey, buddy!

1171
01:06:29,659 --> 01:06:31,991
Everybody, make some noise,
have some fun!

1172
01:06:38,367 --> 01:06:40,164
What's that noise?

1173
01:06:40,203 --> 01:06:42,262
It's a party, Philip.
Midterms, remember?

1174
01:06:42,305 --> 01:06:44,796
They're just blowing off steam.

1175
01:06:44,841 --> 01:06:46,069
You there.

1176
01:06:48,444 --> 01:06:49,741
What's going on here?

1177
01:06:49,779 --> 01:06:53,977
The Melon man is throwing
the greatest party of all time!

1178
01:06:54,016 --> 01:06:57,110
The whole world is there.
It's the best thing...

1179
01:06:57,153 --> 01:06:59,451
that's ever happened to me
in my whole life!

1180
01:06:59,489 --> 01:07:01,787
Oh, God.

1181
01:07:06,162 --> 01:07:08,221
Look at that!

1182
01:07:08,264 --> 01:07:09,424
Listen to that racket.

1183
01:07:09,465 --> 01:07:11,729
This is disgraceful.
I should phone security.

1184
01:07:11,767 --> 01:07:13,428
Oh, Philip.

1185
01:07:18,341 --> 01:07:21,538
Good. Apparently I'm not
the only one around here...

1186
01:07:21,577 --> 01:07:23,135
with a sense of decency.

1187
01:07:29,418 --> 01:07:31,215
Yeah. Cool!

1188
01:07:35,057 --> 01:07:37,491
Did you see...
where are you going?

1189
01:07:37,527 --> 01:07:39,495
Intellectual curiosity, Philip.

1190
01:07:39,529 --> 01:07:40,894
Sounds fun in there.
Come with me.

1191
01:07:40,930 --> 01:07:43,831
- Oh, please!
- Oh, Philip!

1192
01:07:47,703 --> 01:07:50,263
It's a dead man's party

1193
01:07:50,306 --> 01:07:52,467
Who could ask for more

1194
01:07:53,543 --> 01:07:55,477
Everybody's coming

1195
01:07:55,511 --> 01:07:58,412
Leave your body
at the door

1196
01:07:58,447 --> 01:08:02,247
Leave your body and soul
at the door

1197
01:08:03,252 --> 01:08:05,777
Don't run away

1198
01:08:05,821 --> 01:08:08,585
It's only me

1199
01:08:15,498 --> 01:08:17,659
Don't run away

1200
01:08:17,700 --> 01:08:20,999
It's only me, only me

1201
01:08:21,037 --> 01:08:24,302
Don't be afraid

1202
01:08:24,340 --> 01:08:28,800
Of what you can't see

1203
01:08:28,844 --> 01:08:31,005
Say when.

1204
01:08:31,047 --> 01:08:33,641
Right after this drink.

1205
01:08:33,683 --> 01:08:36,049
Hey, what's a bath
without Bubbles?

1206
01:08:36,085 --> 01:08:38,747
Hey, Bubbles,
come over here, will ya?

1207
01:08:41,057 --> 01:08:43,651
Well!

1208
01:08:43,693 --> 01:08:45,923
- Hi there.
- Hi!

1209
01:08:45,962 --> 01:08:48,123
- What's your favorite subject?
- Poetry.

1210
01:08:48,164 --> 01:08:52,157
Really? Maybe you can help me
straighten out my Longfellow.

1211
01:08:55,905 --> 01:08:57,964
Excuse me.
Have you seen Thornton Melon?

1212
01:08:58,007 --> 01:08:59,770
I think he's in there.

1213
01:08:59,809 --> 01:09:00,969
Thanks.

1214
01:09:07,450 --> 01:09:10,317
Excuse me.
Has anyone seen Thornton Melon?

1215
01:09:11,487 --> 01:09:14,081
That's what I call
marine biology.

1216
01:09:14,123 --> 01:09:15,522
Diane!

1217
01:09:17,226 --> 01:09:19,387
Say hello to my nieces.

1218
01:09:20,963 --> 01:09:22,362
Wait a minute!

1219
01:09:27,036 --> 01:09:31,473
Jason? There you are.
I was looking all over for you.

1220
01:09:31,507 --> 01:09:35,568
Jason, are you OK?
I'm sorry about the swim meet.

1221
01:09:35,611 --> 01:09:38,808
Shit. Swim meet.

1222
01:09:38,848 --> 01:09:41,578
Jesus, you think I care
about the swim meet?

1223
01:09:41,617 --> 01:09:43,482
I mean, it's just
a stupid college game.

1224
01:09:43,519 --> 01:09:44,850
It's just bullshit.

1225
01:09:44,887 --> 01:09:46,821
Why are you acting like this?

1226
01:09:46,856 --> 01:09:48,847
I know you don't think
like that.

1227
01:09:48,891 --> 01:09:51,257
Oh, you do?

1228
01:09:51,294 --> 01:09:54,354
Grow up, Valerie.
You think this is real?

1229
01:09:54,397 --> 01:09:57,491
This isn't real.
College is a dream world.

1230
01:09:57,533 --> 01:09:59,262
This is something you do
to pass the time...

1231
01:09:59,302 --> 01:10:01,827
till you go out in the real
world and start buying people.

1232
01:10:01,871 --> 01:10:04,533
Let's go for a walk
and talk this out.

1233
01:10:04,573 --> 01:10:06,666
There you are.

1234
01:10:06,709 --> 01:10:08,700
Can we go? I'm bored.

1235
01:10:08,744 --> 01:10:09,972
Oh, Christ, Osbourne...

1236
01:10:10,012 --> 01:10:12,207
will you just get
your ass outta here?

1237
01:10:12,248 --> 01:10:14,273
What a surprise.
Another shit-faced Melon.

1238
01:10:14,317 --> 01:10:16,478
Do I gotta knock your teeth
down your throat?

1239
01:10:16,519 --> 01:10:19,420
Easy. Your father isn't here
to back you up this time.

1240
01:10:21,424 --> 01:10:22,891
Don't!

1241
01:10:27,263 --> 01:10:28,560
Are you OK?

1242
01:10:28,597 --> 01:10:32,294
Jason! I was lookin' for ya.

1243
01:10:32,335 --> 01:10:35,304
Hey, come here. Where ya goin'?

1244
01:10:35,338 --> 01:10:37,806
Where am I going?

1245
01:10:37,840 --> 01:10:40,536
I'm leaving school, Dad.
One of us has gotta go.

1246
01:10:40,576 --> 01:10:42,771
You're having such a great time.
I'm getting out.

1247
01:10:42,812 --> 01:10:44,279
Why? I don't get it.

1248
01:10:44,313 --> 01:10:46,008
Because you didn't win
the diving meet?

1249
01:10:46,048 --> 01:10:47,811
No, not because I didn't win!

1250
01:10:47,850 --> 01:10:49,545
Because I shouldn't
even have been there.

1251
01:10:49,585 --> 01:10:51,075
Chas told me
you bribed the coach...

1252
01:10:51,120 --> 01:10:52,587
to put me on the team.
Real good!

1253
01:10:52,621 --> 01:10:55,852
What? And you believed him.
I never lied to you in my life.

1254
01:10:55,891 --> 01:10:57,153
I didn't bribe the coach.

1255
01:10:57,193 --> 01:10:58,922
You were on the team
because you deserve it.

1256
01:10:58,961 --> 01:11:00,690
You made it on your own.

1257
01:11:00,730 --> 01:11:02,527
Dad, you don't get it.

1258
01:11:02,565 --> 01:11:04,123
Everything I have
is because of you...

1259
01:11:04,166 --> 01:11:05,326
and because of you...

1260
01:11:05,368 --> 01:11:09,065
I get my astronomy homework
done for me by NASA.

1261
01:11:09,105 --> 01:11:12,131
I just want the best for you.
That's all I ever wanted.

1262
01:11:14,710 --> 01:11:16,371
I did it all for you.

1263
01:11:17,847 --> 01:11:20,372
I know, but you don't know
when to quit.

1264
01:11:20,416 --> 01:11:24,284
I know you came here to help me,
and I really appreciate it...

1265
01:11:24,320 --> 01:11:27,118
and it's really sweet,
and it's really not working.

1266
01:11:27,156 --> 01:11:29,021
Can't you let me just do
something for myself?

1267
01:11:29,058 --> 01:11:31,151
I just want to see you happy.

1268
01:11:31,193 --> 01:11:33,821
Well, take a good look!

1269
01:11:33,863 --> 01:11:37,492
'Cause I was a lot happier
when I was miserable.

1270
01:11:49,111 --> 01:11:50,874
I enjoyed reading that, Susan.

1271
01:11:50,913 --> 01:11:52,210
It's a nice improvement.
Thank you.

1272
01:11:52,248 --> 01:11:54,773
Diane, why'd you fail me?

1273
01:11:54,817 --> 01:11:57,308
I didn't, Thornton.
You failed me.

1274
01:11:57,353 --> 01:12:00,811
- Is it because of last night?
- No. I can accept the fact...

1275
01:12:00,856 --> 01:12:02,824
that you're completely
regressed emotionally...

1276
01:12:02,858 --> 01:12:05,827
but you won't pass my course by
turning in someone else's work.

1277
01:12:05,861 --> 01:12:08,591
What do you think,
someone else wrote this?

1278
01:12:08,631 --> 01:12:11,065
All I know is that you didn't.
That's what disappoints me.

1279
01:12:11,100 --> 01:12:13,159
Whoever did write it...

1280
01:12:13,202 --> 01:12:15,830
doesn't know the first thing
about Kurt Vonnegut.

1281
01:12:15,871 --> 01:12:17,133
And another thing, Vonnegut.

1282
01:12:17,173 --> 01:12:19,573
I'm going to stop payment
on the check.

1283
01:12:19,608 --> 01:12:22,076
What's that? Fuck me?

1284
01:12:22,111 --> 01:12:25,740
Kurt, do you read lips?
Fuck you!

1285
01:12:25,781 --> 01:12:27,772
Next time
I'll call Robert Ludlum.

1286
01:12:31,754 --> 01:12:33,688
Derek, have you seen Jason?

1287
01:12:33,722 --> 01:12:36,691
I think he's on
a three-state killing spree.

1288
01:12:36,725 --> 01:12:38,522
Here's some more
potentially bad news.

1289
01:12:38,561 --> 01:12:41,428
Dean Martin wants to see you
in his office right away.

1290
01:12:41,464 --> 01:12:42,795
Dean Martin.

1291
01:12:44,800 --> 01:12:49,260
And she said, "Let's do it.
The room's already paid for."

1292
01:12:53,409 --> 01:12:57,072
Oh, golly.
I'm afraid we have...

1293
01:12:57,112 --> 01:13:00,980
a potentially unpleasant
situation on our hands here.

1294
01:13:01,016 --> 01:13:04,144
Phil, would you repeat
to Mr. Melon...

1295
01:13:04,186 --> 01:13:07,280
the allegations
that you've made to me?

1296
01:13:07,323 --> 01:13:10,292
It's clear the work you've
handed in is not your own.

1297
01:13:10,326 --> 01:13:12,726
I'm accusing you
of academic fraud.

1298
01:13:12,761 --> 01:13:16,492
Fraud is such an ugly word...

1299
01:13:16,532 --> 01:13:19,467
considering
the financial generosity...

1300
01:13:19,502 --> 01:13:22,494
that Mr. Melon has shown
towards our fine university.

1301
01:13:22,538 --> 01:13:25,234
I think Mr. Melon
should be expelled.

1302
01:13:26,876 --> 01:13:30,039
What are you going
to do about it?

1303
01:13:31,514 --> 01:13:33,641
Well, Thornton...

1304
01:13:33,682 --> 01:13:36,310
I'm only going
to ask you this one time.

1305
01:13:36,352 --> 01:13:39,913
Is the work that
you turned in your own?

1306
01:13:43,726 --> 01:13:46,251
I can't lie to you,
Dean Martin.

1307
01:13:48,831 --> 01:13:50,321
Yes, it is.

1308
01:13:50,366 --> 01:13:52,960
I'm satisfied.

1309
01:13:53,002 --> 01:13:55,163
- Phil?
- I'm outraged.

1310
01:13:55,204 --> 01:13:58,264
Gee whiz, Phil!
I just asked the man...

1311
01:13:58,307 --> 01:14:00,434
if the work was his,
and he said yes.

1312
01:14:00,476 --> 01:14:03,104
What do you want me to do,
torture him?

1313
01:14:04,547 --> 01:14:07,880
I suggest a comprehensive
oral examination...

1314
01:14:07,917 --> 01:14:10,317
conducted by all of
Mr. Melon's professors.

1315
01:14:10,352 --> 01:14:11,819
Oral examination?

1316
01:14:11,854 --> 01:14:15,381
Yes. If you've done the work
you say you have...

1317
01:14:15,424 --> 01:14:18,723
there should be no problem,
should there?

1318
01:14:20,596 --> 01:14:22,962
Hey, Jase.

1319
01:14:22,998 --> 01:14:25,558
Hey, Lou. How you doin'?

1320
01:14:25,601 --> 01:14:27,466
Come here.
I want to tell you something.

1321
01:14:27,503 --> 01:14:28,629
What?

1322
01:14:28,671 --> 01:14:30,901
You were pretty hard
on your father last night.

1323
01:14:30,940 --> 01:14:33,340
I know, but the guy
doesn't understand.

1324
01:14:33,375 --> 01:14:36,071
I know your pop thirty years.
He understands.

1325
01:14:36,111 --> 01:14:38,477
He's a nice guy,
and he's tough.

1326
01:14:38,514 --> 01:14:42,575
Like me.
I'm nice, and I'm tough.

1327
01:14:42,618 --> 01:14:45,143
I'll give you an idea
what I mean.

1328
01:14:45,187 --> 01:14:47,815
My two boys... I put one
through college...

1329
01:14:47,856 --> 01:14:49,687
and the other
I put through a wall.

1330
01:14:51,160 --> 01:14:53,151
Your papa loves you.

1331
01:14:54,430 --> 01:14:57,991
He's lookin' out for ya.
Look out for him.

1332
01:15:23,525 --> 01:15:24,822
What's goin' on?

1333
01:15:24,860 --> 01:15:27,624
I'm leavin'. I'm sorry, Jason.

1334
01:15:27,663 --> 01:15:30,894
This college thing
was a big mistake.

1335
01:15:30,933 --> 01:15:33,766
- So you're gonna give up?
- I can't win.

1336
01:15:33,802 --> 01:15:36,430
They want me to take oral exams
in all my subjects.

1337
01:15:36,472 --> 01:15:38,940
If I don't take them,
they'll kick me out.

1338
01:15:38,974 --> 01:15:41,534
And if I take 'em,
who knows where they'll kick me.

1339
01:15:44,313 --> 01:15:46,679
Hey, Dad, you remember
what you told me...

1340
01:15:46,715 --> 01:15:48,842
when I told you
I wanted to quit?

1341
01:15:48,884 --> 01:15:52,285
You told me that a man
without an education is nothing.

1342
01:15:52,321 --> 01:15:53,413
I can't do it.

1343
01:15:53,455 --> 01:15:54,945
You can do anything
you want to do.

1344
01:15:54,990 --> 01:15:58,118
You can do anything
you want in life.

1345
01:15:58,160 --> 01:16:00,128
Remember, you're a Melon.

1346
01:16:04,133 --> 01:16:06,931
Don't quit. I'll help you.

1347
01:17:33,422 --> 01:17:35,686
Before we begin...

1348
01:17:35,724 --> 01:17:39,216
I would just like to thank
each and every professor here...

1349
01:17:39,261 --> 01:17:44,198
for taking time out of
his/her extremely busy schedule.

1350
01:17:44,233 --> 01:17:47,327
And a special thanks, of course,
to Mr. Thornton Melon...

1351
01:17:47,369 --> 01:17:50,463
who I don't have to remind
anyone is the donor...

1352
01:17:50,506 --> 01:17:53,407
of our new
Melon School of Business.

1353
01:18:01,784 --> 01:18:03,752
We're wasting time.

1354
01:18:03,786 --> 01:18:06,414
Sorry, Phil.

1355
01:18:06,455 --> 01:18:09,754
Now, Mr. Melon,
you'll have three hours...

1356
01:18:09,792 --> 01:18:11,760
to complete the examination.

1357
01:18:11,794 --> 01:18:16,561
If you fail any part of it,
you will be expelled.

1358
01:18:16,598 --> 01:18:19,294
Mr. Melon, do you understand?

1359
01:18:21,170 --> 01:18:23,468
- The Council of Trent.
- Excuse me?

1360
01:18:23,505 --> 01:18:25,029
I missed the question.

1361
01:18:25,073 --> 01:18:26,904
We haven't begun yet.

1362
01:18:29,077 --> 01:18:32,103
Well, Dr. Barbay,
I suppose you're up first.

1363
01:18:46,595 --> 01:18:51,055
I have only one question
for Mr. Melon...

1364
01:18:55,504 --> 01:18:58,667
in 27 parts.

1365
01:19:01,343 --> 01:19:04,073
I'd like to break him
in 27 parts.

1366
01:19:04,112 --> 01:19:05,477
Excuse me?

1367
01:19:05,514 --> 01:19:06,879
No, nothin', nothin'.

1368
01:19:09,918 --> 01:19:13,285
Discuss the foundations of
modern global business systems.

1369
01:19:13,322 --> 01:19:16,086
Part one: Define
and differentiate...

1370
01:19:16,124 --> 01:19:18,092
the three economic
philosophies...

1371
01:19:18,126 --> 01:19:20,321
of capitalism, socialism
and communism...

1372
01:19:20,362 --> 01:19:23,889
as pertains to:
A... management fundamentals;

1373
01:19:23,932 --> 01:19:26,093
B... organizing and staffing;

1374
01:19:26,134 --> 01:19:28,125
C... labor management;

1375
01:19:28,170 --> 01:19:30,900
and D... production
and operations.

1376
01:19:30,939 --> 01:19:33,965
Part two...

1377
01:19:34,009 --> 01:19:36,978
Are you getting
all this, Mr. Melon?

1378
01:19:37,012 --> 01:19:39,776
Yeah. It's a piece o' cake.

1379
01:19:42,417 --> 01:19:44,851
Jason?

1380
01:19:49,858 --> 01:19:51,826
Valerie.

1381
01:19:51,860 --> 01:19:56,422
I wanted to apologize
for the other night...

1382
01:19:56,465 --> 01:20:00,868
my behavior
and the things I said.

1383
01:20:00,903 --> 01:20:02,495
And to thank you...

1384
01:20:02,537 --> 01:20:05,734
for your behavior
and the things you said.

1385
01:20:06,875 --> 01:20:10,402
I'm really sorry.

1386
01:20:10,445 --> 01:20:12,470
And I'm really
in love with you...

1387
01:20:12,514 --> 01:20:14,277
and I really have been
for a very long time.

1388
01:20:14,316 --> 01:20:17,444
And I can't believe
I'm saying this.

1389
01:20:17,486 --> 01:20:20,387
I don't want
to embarrass you...

1390
01:20:20,422 --> 01:20:23,755
or make you feel
uncomfortable with me...

1391
01:20:23,792 --> 01:20:26,317
but...

1392
01:20:26,361 --> 01:20:32,061
I've been needing to tell you
this for a very long time.

1393
01:20:34,836 --> 01:20:37,066
Are you aware that
that's the most...

1394
01:20:37,105 --> 01:20:39,630
you've ever said to me
at one time?

1395
01:20:39,675 --> 01:20:43,042
Except, of course, for the time
that you were ravingly drunk.

1396
01:20:44,780 --> 01:20:46,270
I love you, too.

1397
01:21:08,403 --> 01:21:12,134
In response
to Roman numeral 27...

1398
01:21:12,174 --> 01:21:15,143
section three, part two...

1399
01:21:15,177 --> 01:21:18,908
of subset D...
of the question...

1400
01:21:18,947 --> 01:21:21,347
the answer is...

1401
01:21:22,417 --> 01:21:24,078
Mr. Melon?

1402
01:21:31,793 --> 01:21:33,021
Mr. Melon?

1403
01:21:33,061 --> 01:21:36,895
Hey, relax. This man's been put
under a lot of pressure.

1404
01:21:36,932 --> 01:21:38,900
Let's take it easy on him.

1405
01:21:38,934 --> 01:21:41,095
Say it! Say it!

1406
01:21:42,571 --> 01:21:45,563
The answer is... four?

1407
01:21:52,781 --> 01:21:53,770
Right.

1408
01:22:00,822 --> 01:22:02,983
Dr. Turner?

1409
01:22:07,863 --> 01:22:10,331
Hold it. That's it.

1410
01:22:10,365 --> 01:22:11,957
I can't take it no more.

1411
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:16,630
I feel like I just gave birth
to an accountant.

1412
01:22:17,973 --> 01:22:19,463
Wait a minute, Thornton.

1413
01:22:31,386 --> 01:22:35,220
Thornton, do you remember
when we discussed...

1414
01:22:35,257 --> 01:22:36,815
the Dylan Thomas poem...

1415
01:22:36,858 --> 01:22:39,383
"Do Not Go Gentle
Into That Good Night"?

1416
01:22:39,428 --> 01:22:41,453
I don't know.

1417
01:22:41,496 --> 01:22:43,896
No. Maybe.

1418
01:22:43,932 --> 01:22:45,832
Thornton, think.

1419
01:22:45,867 --> 01:22:47,698
What's going on here?

1420
01:22:49,104 --> 01:22:52,562
Philip, relax. It's my turn.

1421
01:22:56,978 --> 01:22:58,343
Do you remember it?

1422
01:23:00,048 --> 01:23:03,211
"Do not go gentle into...

1423
01:23:03,251 --> 01:23:05,811
"into that good night.

1424
01:23:07,989 --> 01:23:10,719
"Old age should burn
and rage...

1425
